still plan to force insurance companies to
diverse from Iran, which I support.

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:25.109
I commend you for standing behind that since
the insurance industry has been coming after

00:34:25.109 --> 00:34:30.079
you for it.
And I know that they are -- you know, they

00:34:30.079 --> 00:34:36.250
hired the campaign team that did Prop. 8 to,
you know, plant news articles and op eds against

00:34:36.250 --> 00:34:40.249
you.
And I'm just wondering, like, what your view

00:34:40.249 --> 00:34:45.429
is of how we need to reform the influence
of business on the political process.

00:34:45.429 --> 00:34:52.259
You talked about public employee unions.
But in my view, the -- you know, the runaway

00:34:52.259 --> 00:34:58.700
power is, you know, independent expenditures
from corporations in California and these

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:02.920
other kinds of attacks, like the ones against
you, that aren't even disclosed.

00:35:02.920 --> 00:35:07.249
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Well, thank you for asking
an insurance question.

00:35:07.249 --> 00:35:13.630
So, as insurance commissioner, one of my most
important duties is to make sure that insurance

00:35:13.630 --> 00:35:17.701
companies stay financially sound.
And I mentioned my over 1,000 employees.

00:35:17.701 --> 00:35:22.770
A big chunk of them are in financial surveillance,
where we monitor the 1300 insurance companies

00:35:22.770 --> 00:35:26.089
that do business in California very closely.
In the middle of the financial meltdown, we

00:35:26.089 --> 00:35:29.109
were making sure that they stayed financially
strong.

00:35:29.109 --> 00:35:32.650
I'm pleased to report, we've been able to
keep most insurance companies safe and secure.

00:35:32.650 --> 00:35:36.770
And so when you turn in a legitimate claim,
you know, after you pay -- you know, you pay

00:35:36.770 --> 00:35:38.789
for your auto insurance and your health care
insurance and your earthquake insurance year

00:35:38.789 --> 00:35:41.259
after year after year.
If you have a legitimate claim, there better

00:35:41.259 --> 00:35:45.400
be money there to pay off a legitimate claim.
That's why my financial surveillance duties

00:35:45.400 --> 00:35:47.920
are important.
When I was looking at the financial health

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:53.200
of insurance companies, I found that they
have this massive investment portfolio, $4

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:56.599
trillion is the global investment portfolio
for insurance companies.

00:35:56.599 --> 00:35:58.440
They're the largest investor group in the
world.

00:35:58.440 --> 00:36:06.470
At least 6 billion invested in Iran, in their
military, nuclear, and defense sectors.

00:36:06.470 --> 00:36:10.480
It's just wrong.
And so I am pushing them as hard as I can

00:36:10.480 --> 00:36:15.759
with all of my powers and duties and persuasive
skills to get them to divest.

00:36:15.759 --> 00:36:19.500
They can do better than that.
They have no business really being -- investing

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:22.119
in companies that are propping up the Iranian
regime.

00:36:22.119 --> 00:36:26.160
I think the Iranian regime, it's crystal clear
they're a big danger to its own people, to

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:32.420
its neighbors, and to our national security.
Now, $6 billion turns out to be 2 or 3% of

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:36.170
Iran's gross domestic product.
It's a very small, tiny percentage of their

00:36:36.170 --> 00:36:39.099
investment portfolio.
They could easily divest here.

00:36:39.099 --> 00:36:45.359
And so, of the 1300 insurance companies, I
have gotten over 750 to agree to not only

00:36:45.359 --> 00:36:50.049
voluntarily divest, but to not invest in any
new investments in Iran in the future.

00:36:50.049 --> 00:36:54.430
Now, there's a few hundred insurance companies
that are fighting back hard.

00:36:54.430 --> 00:36:59.470
They just want to maximize their returns independent
of the impact that they're having on our national

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:01.480
security.
And I'm going to fight them on it.

00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:06.970
And the fact that they're pushing back on
me so hard should tell you something.

00:37:06.970 --> 00:37:11.240
Republican or Democrat, doesn't matter, I
will do what it takes to stand up to insurance

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:15.049
companies to make sure that they fulfill all
of their legal obligations to policyholders.

00:37:15.049 --> 00:37:18.660
When they cancel people's insurance improperly,
I am going to go after them, make sure they

00:37:18.660 --> 00:37:22.259
reinstate people's health insurance, even
though they canceled it sometimes in the middle

00:37:22.259 --> 00:37:25.231
of major health procedures.
In the case of Iran, I'm going to do what

00:37:25.231 --> 00:37:27.539
it takes to make sure that they purge their
investments.

00:37:27.539 --> 00:37:34.220
And if I can just say, Google, you know, what
you did in China, I'm sure it was a lot of

00:37:34.220 --> 00:37:38.560
discussion, maybe a big controversy even inside
of Google, I don't really know, I only know

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:41.519
what I read.
But I've got to tell you how proud I am to

00:37:41.519 --> 00:37:44.779
know you all.
I think what you did in China was a fantastic

00:37:44.779 --> 00:37:47.630
thing.
There's a big difference between focusing

00:37:47.630 --> 00:37:50.869
on just the very short term and focusing in
on the long term.

00:37:50.869 --> 00:37:56.130
And I suspect that people who focus on the
long term, where, you know, censorship is

00:37:56.130 --> 00:38:02.359
wrong, investments in Iran are wrong.
If you do the right thing, I'm pretty confident

00:38:02.359 --> 00:38:07.329
it will pay off for folks who do that.
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Next question.

00:38:07.329 --> 00:38:10.980
&gt;&gt;&gt; Hello.
I'd like to ask about Prop. 13.

00:38:10.980 --> 00:38:18.410
As a legal immigrant to the U.S., I find it
really bizarre that I have to pay ten times

00:38:18.410 --> 00:38:23.589
as much as my neighbor for essentially the
same home.

00:38:23.589 --> 00:38:29.769
And I don't understand why I need to be punished
for coming to work in Silicon Valley.

00:38:29.769 --> 00:38:34.231
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: And this is a question about
Prop. 13; right?

00:38:34.231 --> 00:38:36.099
1978.
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Yeah, Prop. 13 is very controversial.

00:38:36.099 --> 00:38:40.559
I support Prop. 13, though, for one basic
reason.

00:38:40.559 --> 00:38:45.310
It provides predictability for home owners.
So even though people across the street from

00:38:45.310 --> 00:38:49.980
each other might be paying different rates,
on the other hand, when people get into their

00:38:49.980 --> 00:38:54.069
homes, they know the situation.
When you bought your home, you know what the

00:38:54.069 --> 00:38:56.730
property tax was going to be and you know
what your mortgage is going to be, and you

00:38:56.730 --> 00:38:59.039
run the numbers.
Can you afford it or not.

00:38:59.039 --> 00:39:04.290
And then Prop. 13 starts to benefit you.
Once you're a home owner, then you know what

00:39:04.290 --> 00:39:08.529
your property taxes are going to be in a very
predictable way for many decades to come.

00:39:08.529 --> 00:39:12.910
And that will benefit new the longer term.
What I like about Prop. 13, then, is it doesn't

00:39:12.910 --> 00:39:17.119
drive people out of their homes.
When it passed in 1978, property taxes were

00:39:17.119 --> 00:39:20.539
being ratcheted up.
And some people were on fixed incomes and

00:39:20.539 --> 00:39:24.410
they were having to sell their homes because
they didn't have that predictability.

00:39:24.410 --> 00:39:28.039
I think having this cap on property taxes
is a good thing.

00:39:28.039 --> 00:39:33.499
The other important part about Prop. 13 is
that it requires a two-thirds vote to increase

00:39:33.499 --> 00:39:37.400
taxes in California in most cases.
I think that's a good thing, too.

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:41.450
I know that's also controversial.
But the fact is even with the two-thirds voting

00:39:41.450 --> 00:39:46.019
rules, you have to ask yourself, if we made
it easier to pass taxes, if we lowered that

00:39:46.019 --> 00:39:50.489
two-thirds to something less than two-thirds,
would taxes go up or down?

00:39:50.489 --> 00:39:53.900
Of course they're going to go up.
Now, even though the two-thirds voting rules

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:57.661
have been in place now since 1978, do we have
low taxes?

00:39:57.661 --> 00:40:02.239
No.
Now, property taxes, even with Prop. 13, property

00:40:02.239 --> 00:40:07.170
taxes are at the national average, median.
All the other taxes are the highest in the

00:40:07.170 --> 00:40:11.390
country, practically, highest sales taxes,
income taxes, vehicle license fees.

00:40:11.390 --> 00:40:15.700
We have gas taxes, beer taxes, wine taxes,
phone taxes, capital gains taxes.

00:40:15.700 --> 00:40:19.509
We have 900 different taxes and fees.
If you add them up and divide by the number

00:40:19.509 --> 00:40:24.780
of people, you get the per capita tax burden,
50% higher here in California than nearby

00:40:24.780 --> 00:40:28.470
western states.
I mean, no wonder 3,000 people a week pick

00:40:28.470 --> 00:40:32.809
up and leave the state of California each
and every week, because this place is way

00:40:32.809 --> 00:40:35.989
overtaxed.
I would never change those two-thirds voting

00:40:35.989 --> 00:40:41.349
rules, because our taxes will even go up higher.
I think taxes have to come down, not up.

00:40:41.349 --> 00:40:46.130
That's why, actually, one of the key center
pieces of my campaign is actually to cut taxes.

00:40:46.130 --> 00:40:51.760
I'm proposing a 10% cut in sales taxes, a
10% cut in corporate taxes, a 10% cut in personal

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:57.130
income taxes, every bracket, and a 50% cut
in capital gains taxes.

00:40:57.130 --> 00:41:01.801
People ask me all the time, how on Earth can
we afford a tax cut when we can't balance

00:41:01.801 --> 00:41:05.739
the budget as it is.
Honestly, the answer is, we can't afford not

00:41:05.739 --> 00:41:08.670
to.
We need lower tax rates so we can become competitive

00:41:08.670 --> 00:41:12.420
again.
And then the tax base will increase in size

00:41:12.420 --> 00:41:17.140
as jobs return to California, and then the
tax revenues go up, not down.

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:19.359
And just briefly, we did an economic analysis
of this.

00:41:19.359 --> 00:41:24.380
We looked at the other 49 states.
We found a dozen examples of when people -- when

00:41:24.380 --> 00:41:28.819
states actually cut taxes across the board.
Tax revenues went up, not down, immediately

00:41:28.819 --> 00:41:32.430
after the tax cut.
We need to bring jobs back to California.

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:35.449
It's essential.
