00:42:09.859 --> 00:42:14.890
I got to the Department of Insurance, I had
a budget deficit of about $5 million, structural

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:17.079
deficit.
Now I have this huge surplus.

00:42:17.079 --> 00:42:20.319
And I've taken the surplus, and I mentioned,
tax cuts.

00:42:20.319 --> 00:42:24.369
I've cut taxes twice on insurance agents and
brokers and companies that fund my department

00:42:24.369 --> 00:42:29.420
to the tune of millions and millions of dollars.
If I hadn't been able to reduce my operating

00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:32.430
expenses by 15%, I would never have been able
to generate the surplus.

00:42:32.430 --> 00:42:37.029
This has all been documented.
And she's just wrong.

00:42:37.029 --> 00:42:39.369
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Our next question.
Yes, sir.

00:42:39.369 --> 00:42:43.499
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Which, by the way, you may
be looking at the only person in Sacramento

00:42:43.499 --> 00:42:49.079
history that's ever downsized anything.
And right now, downsizing is not really the

00:42:49.079 --> 00:42:50.359
perfect word.
It's really right-sizing.

00:42:50.359 --> 00:42:54.720
I know you're in the growth mode.
But in Sacramento, they've been in the growth

00:42:54.720 --> 00:42:57.890
mode for 20 years, unfortunately.
Now they need to go into the right-sizing

00:42:57.890 --> 00:43:00.810
mode.
We need to balance the budget with no more

00:43:00.810 --> 00:43:06.369
taxes, no more gimmicks, no more borrowing.
We can do it, but we're going to have to go

00:43:06.369 --> 00:43:10.979
through every line of the budget, like I have,
all 1200 pages and overhaul and modernize

00:43:10.979 --> 00:43:13.009
the entire state of California.
It hasn't been done.

00:43:13.009 --> 00:43:16.890
It can be done.
It's essential that we get it done.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:20.440
&gt;&gt;&gt; Thank you for coming.
You mentioned the $20 billion deficit that

00:43:20.440 --> 00:43:25.309
our state is facing, and you also touched
on, with the severe gridlock between the legislature

00:43:25.309 --> 00:43:31.549
and traditionally the governor's mansion,
the challenge in cutting costs and programs.

00:43:31.549 --> 00:43:35.789
So with your tax cuts that you're proposing,
can you talk a bit more specifically about

00:43:35.789 --> 00:43:39.359
how you plan to perhaps bring in more revenue
for the state.

00:43:39.359 --> 00:43:42.509
Are you looking to perhaps stimulate certain
sectors of the economy through -- for instance,

00:43:42.509 --> 00:43:46.970
we've had the first-time home buyer's credit
that's been in effect the last year and a

00:43:46.970 --> 00:43:49.819
half or so.
What other specific credits or policies do

00:43:49.819 --> 00:43:53.140
you have in mind to perhaps drive up the revenue
for the state?

00:43:53.140 --> 00:43:56.070
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: This is a major difference
between Meg Whitman and me, by the way.

00:43:56.070 --> 00:43:58.579
I mentioned before some of difference in our
background, but we have some major differences

00:43:58.579 --> 00:44:02.380
on policy.
Meg Whitman definitely is a fan of targeted

00:44:02.380 --> 00:44:06.610
tax cuts, you know, where she wants to stimulate
certain sectors.

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:10.200
I've got to tell you, I am completely opposed
to that.

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:14.680
The idea of empowering a bunch of Sacramento
politicians to pick winners and losers, just

00:44:14.680 --> 00:44:20.089
absolutely wrong, in my opinion.
I'm proposing across-the-board tax cuts so

00:44:20.089 --> 00:44:23.240
that everyone benefits, every consumer, every
small business.

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:28.510
We want to encourage more people to come here.
My last company, SnapTrack, you know, I came

00:44:28.510 --> 00:44:30.900
here from Texas, I think I've said "y'all"
a couple of times.

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:34.450
I catch myself, I'm giving away where I come
from.

00:44:34.450 --> 00:44:38.539
I came from Texas 30 years ago because this
was the best place on the planet to start

00:44:38.539 --> 00:44:43.049
and grow companies.
And we're not that way anymore.

00:44:43.049 --> 00:44:45.729
We have to get back to that.
I ran some numbers.

00:44:45.729 --> 00:44:50.250
If I would have started my company back in
Texas rather than California, I had 100 employees

00:44:50.250 --> 00:44:54.970
when I sold to Qualcomm.
And we did sell for a billion dollars.

00:44:54.970 --> 00:44:57.609
It was in the Mercury News, so there's no
secreted.

00:44:57.609 --> 00:45:00.630
Qualcomm is a public company.
All my employees were shareholders.

00:45:00.630 --> 00:45:04.190
It was a great thing.
But I did run some numbers.

00:45:04.190 --> 00:45:09.640
If I had started my company in Texas rather
than here, the state of California would be

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:15.109
out $100 million, meaning that my employees
paid $100 million in state and local taxes.

00:45:15.109 --> 00:45:18.619
And so it really makes a difference where
companies set up and grow.

00:45:18.619 --> 00:45:21.529
Eric, we did -- we did back of the envelope
on Google.

00:45:21.529 --> 00:45:25.150
It's hard to know for sure.
But we ran some numbers.

00:45:25.150 --> 00:45:31.839
If Google would have started the company in
Nevada rather than in California, we estimate

00:45:31.839 --> 00:45:37.990
at least $10 billion difference, meaning that
if you weren't a California company, California

00:45:37.990 --> 00:45:40.599
would be $10 billion more in the hole.
You all have paid --

00:45:40.599 --> 00:45:43.559
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: In other words, we would have
had $10 billion more had we gone to Nevada?

00:45:43.559 --> 00:45:45.529
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Let's get --

00:45:45.529 --> 00:45:49.099
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Let's get the math right.
When are we moving to Nevada, guys?

00:45:49.099 --> 00:45:55.420
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Since 1998, Google as a company
and its employees have paid $10 billion in

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:58.630
state and local taxes.
So thank you for being in California.

00:45:58.630 --> 00:46:02.690
Thank goodness you are here in California.
But it all has to do with creating an environment

00:46:02.690 --> 00:46:05.779
so that the next Google or the next SnapTrack
wants to start here.

00:46:05.779 --> 00:46:11.171
And right now, we have an environment with
super-high taxes, burdensome regulations,

00:46:11.171 --> 00:46:18.710
and, I'm telling you, there is a huge exodus.
Cisco, quote, we haven't created a new tech

00:46:18.710 --> 00:46:22.869
job in California in a decade.
Intel standing right next to President Obama,

00:46:22.869 --> 00:46:27.140
the CEO of Intel, talking about all of the
expansion of chip manufacturing in this country,

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:30.400
none in California.
Hewlett Packard, California is no-man's land

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:34.680
when it comes to new manufacturing.
NUMMI, the last automobile manufacturing plant

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:40.739
in California, just closed down last week.
5,000 jobs gone, 25,000 supplier jobs.

00:46:40.739 --> 00:46:44.619
Why?
Taxes are too high; regulations are too burdensome.

00:46:44.619 --> 00:46:48.300
That's why I'm proposing sweeping, bold changes.
Half measures won't do here.

00:46:48.300 --> 00:46:53.539
&gt;&gt;&gt; Thanks for coming here.
A while back, you were talking about how you

00:46:53.539 --> 00:46:58.040
are clear about your issues so that when you
get elected, you'll have the mandate.

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:00.520
And I really appreciate your being straight
about that.

00:47:00.520 --> 00:47:06.589
My question is -- and you also talked about
keeping the two-thirds requirement in the

00:47:06.589 --> 00:47:11.020
legislature for the budget.
Now, if anything -- if we have learned anything

00:47:11.020 --> 00:47:17.170
in the last one year, right, getting elected
based on an issue and -- you know, does not

00:47:17.170 --> 00:47:22.180
give you an easy way to enact things.
Now, you're promising all these tax cuts,

00:47:22.180 --> 00:47:26.519
but are you sure you're going to get more
than two-thirds of the legislature actually

00:47:26.519 --> 00:47:31.750
voting for it other than just sending it,
like, across veto messages?

00:47:31.750 --> 00:47:36.119
How are you going to do that?
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Your question's really a

00:47:36.119 --> 00:47:38.329
great question.
And the essence of your question is, how on

00:47:38.329 --> 00:47:43.430
Earth are you going to get anything done?
And, Eric, you asked a form of that question

00:47:43.430 --> 00:47:46.279
earlier.
And it's -- there's no easy answers.

00:47:46.279 --> 00:47:49.569
I know this: If we don't try, it'll never
get fixed.

00:47:49.569 --> 00:47:53.319
I also know that there's nothing keeping us
from fixing these problems other than political

00:47:53.319 --> 00:47:57.200
failure and leadership failure.
So we're in the middle of a meltdown, which

00:47:57.200 --> 00:48:01.789
creates rare opportunities.
A few years ago, I don't think my bold, sweeping

00:48:01.789 --> 00:48:05.749
reforms would have much of a chance.
Maybe a few years from now, we won't need

00:48:05.749 --> 00:48:08.989
to be so aggressive.
But right now, we're bankrupt.

00:48:08.989 --> 00:48:12.819
And people are suffering.
Do you know that the unemployment right now

00:48:12.819 --> 00:48:17.069
is officially 12.5%?
If you add in all the people who are -- who

00:48:17.069 --> 00:48:22.380
have quit looking for jobs, plus all the people
who have part-time jobs but need full-time

00:48:22.380 --> 00:48:27.029
jobs, that's 20%.
So 4 million Californians are either unemployed

00:48:27.029 --> 00:48:29.839
or underemployed.
That's depression-level misery.

00:48:29.839 --> 00:48:34.869
When you have a situation like that, where
Republicans and Democrats and Independents,

00:48:34.869 --> 00:48:40.420
everyone agrees, the state's broken, and we
need to fix it, under that kind of environment,

00:48:40.420 --> 00:48:44.749
the legislature is going to pay attention,
especially given how clear I am in my campaign.

00:48:44.749 --> 00:48:48.400
If I'm elected, it will provide that extra
political clout.

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:52.809
But I'll say this, if I'm blocked and the
legislature simply doesn't implement these

00:48:52.809 --> 00:48:57.809
critical reforms, which, by the way, I still
maintain, it's unthinkable that we can't get

00:48:57.809 --> 00:49:00.549
this state fixed.
And we don't have much more time.

00:49:00.549 --> 00:49:03.160
We're going to get steam rolled in this global
economy.

00:49:03.160 --> 00:49:06.549
We are getting steamrolled.
We need to move along at an urgent pace.

00:49:06.549 --> 00:49:11.950
If the legislature doesn't fix these problems
after I propose them after I get elected governor,

00:49:11.950 --> 00:49:16.299
then I will take single-issue ballot initiatives
directly to the voters.

00:49:16.299 --> 00:49:19.400
If we have to, the voters will have to take
the state back.

00:49:19.400 --> 00:49:24.440
There are some very specific, simple, short
and sweet ballot initiatives that I will put

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:27.689
in front of the voters in order to get the
reforms that we need.

00:49:27.689 --> 00:49:29.589
&gt;&gt;&gt; Can we ask follow-up questions?
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Of course.

00:49:29.589 --> 00:49:33.569
Go ahead.
&gt;&gt;&gt; If there's one person you remind me of,

00:49:33.569 --> 00:49:37.849
it's Obama, like, a candidate who --
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: That's probably not helpful

00:49:37.849 --> 00:49:41.749
in the Republican primary.
But we'll take that.

00:49:41.749 --> 00:49:49.230
&gt;&gt;&gt; A candidate promising sweeping reforms,
you know, claiming that when he gets elected,

00:49:49.230 --> 00:49:54.109
he'll have a mandate to do it.
And then going to face supermajority requirements

00:49:54.109 --> 00:49:58.509
in the legislature.
And, you know, I don't know how you square

00:49:58.509 --> 00:50:04.589
your own opposition to the health care reform
with what you're promising now and what you

00:50:04.589 --> 00:50:06.880
are saying about how you're going to handle
it later.

00:50:06.880 --> 00:50:11.950
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: It's one of these things
where if you don't try, it'll never get fixed.

00:50:11.950 --> 00:50:16.880
So I know I -- it's like my startup companies.
The probability of success at the beginning

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:20.380
was small.
And then over time, I built the confidence

00:50:20.380 --> 00:50:23.190
of my venture capital exists they invested
more money over time.

00:50:23.190 --> 00:50:26.839
And over time, the probability of success
really ratcheted up.

00:50:26.839 --> 00:50:31.410
Here we have a situation where the state of
California is a mess, and we have to start

00:50:31.410 --> 00:50:34.170
taking some big, bold steps in order to fix
it.

00:50:34.170 --> 00:50:38.160
It's going to be very difficult.
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Thank you very much.

00:50:38.160 --> 00:50:42.950
Sir, you have the honor of the last question.
&gt;&gt;&gt; It's great.

00:50:42.950 --> 00:50:45.009
Because I'm torn between two.
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Well, you can have two questions,

00:50:45.009 --> 00:50:46.589
then.
&gt;&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:50:46.589 --> 00:50:50.479
First question I have is sort of still a follow-up
along the same lines.

00:50:50.479 --> 00:50:54.329
You talked about the mandate.
Governor Schwarzenegger certainly talked about

00:50:54.329 --> 00:50:58.309
it.
Arguably, he had it because of the virtue

00:50:58.309 --> 00:51:01.690
of the recall.
No offense intended, but you're probably not

00:51:01.690 --> 00:51:05.559
as popular as he is, you know, so you have
an even more --

00:51:05.559 --> 00:51:07.410
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: I'm more popular now than
he is.

00:51:07.410 --> 00:51:11.549
&gt;&gt;&gt; That may be.
But, you know, you'll have even more of an

00:51:11.549 --> 00:51:15.309
uphill battle against the legislature than
he did because of that fact.

00:51:15.309 --> 00:51:17.560
How do you see yourself as being different
from him?

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:21.450
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: It's, again, a really good
question.

00:51:21.450 --> 00:51:26.200
Voters have a right to be very skeptical and
cynical, because they've heard this before.

00:51:26.200 --> 00:51:30.390
This is what Schwarzenegger said a few years
ago, and here we are in worse shape.

00:51:30.390 --> 00:51:33.990
Now, I'm a pretty good friend of Governor
Schwarzenegger.

00:51:33.990 --> 00:51:37.550
But, honestly, we're in worse shape than when
he started by a lot.

00:51:37.550 --> 00:51:40.989
Unemployment rate's double; debt's through
the roof.

00:51:40.989 --> 00:51:45.769
Now, his heart's in the rate place.
I really do think that.

00:51:45.769 --> 00:51:50.319
But the fact is, when he tried to go after
these fundamental structural reforms, he tried

00:51:50.319 --> 00:51:53.630
to bite off too much in 2005 during that special
election.

00:51:53.630 --> 00:52:00.999
And there were some flaws in some of the ballot
initiatives that were pointed out by the opponents.

00:52:00.999 --> 00:52:05.279
And then he lost his appetite for reform.
That's not me.

00:52:05.279 --> 00:52:09.960
I can promise you this: I'm going to have
the tenacity, the backbone, and the will and

00:52:09.960 --> 00:52:13.059
the drive to not budge.
You lose the first time.

00:52:13.059 --> 00:52:14.710
You try it again.
You lose again.

00:52:14.710 --> 00:52:17.999
You try it again.
We have to get this fixed.

00:52:17.999 --> 00:52:20.549
I think there's probably not much of a debate
on what we need to do.

00:52:20.549 --> 00:52:24.069
Our taxes are too high.
Our spending is out of control.

00:52:24.069 --> 00:52:28.969
The regulatory system doesn't allow for permits
to be obtained to build manufacturing facilities.

00:52:28.969 --> 00:52:32.880
We have to overhaul that.
Our education system is micromanaged by the

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:38.819
legislature.
Let's' go on here is the problem, here's the

00:52:38.819 --> 00:52:41.660
solution.
And then let's figure out how to put political

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:45.250
pressure on the legislature to get the job
done.

00:52:45.250 --> 00:52:53.979
Here's one idea I have that's pretty controversial,
but I'll take it to the voters if I have to.

00:52:53.979 --> 00:52:58.289
That's to convert the legislature from full-time
to part-time.

00:52:58.289 --> 00:53:00.469
I know that's counterintuitive to some of
you.

00:53:00.469 --> 00:53:03.509
I would convert it to no time if I can get
away with it.

00:53:03.509 --> 00:53:06.329
I'm kidding about that.
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: They make fewer laws because

00:53:06.329 --> 00:53:08.950
they're in office less.
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: That's a fact.

00:53:08.950 --> 00:53:12.420
Right now there are thousands and thousands
of pieces of legislation that flow through

00:53:12.420 --> 00:53:15.089
the legislature.
Now, A few months ago, for example, in the

00:53:15.089 --> 00:53:19.059
middle of the financial meltdown, they actually
debated whether they should form a blueberry

00:53:19.059 --> 00:53:21.979
commission to promote the sales of blueberries.
Now, hey, --

00:53:21.979 --> 00:53:24.890
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: You don't like blueberries?
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: I love blueberries.

00:53:24.890 --> 00:53:27.809
I just don't think we need a new commission.
Especially, we don't need the legislature

00:53:27.809 --> 00:53:31.040
focusing on it.
The other advantage of a part-time legislature

00:53:31.040 --> 00:53:35.309
 -- which exists, by the way, in 42 states
have a part-time legislature -- is you change

00:53:35.309 --> 00:53:39.150
the mix of people in the legislature.
Part of the part-time legislature proposal

00:53:39.150 --> 00:53:42.261
is to cut their salaries in half.
That would force people on the legislature

00:53:42.261 --> 00:53:47.510
to have a job someplace else.
That would be a good thing, people who actually

00:53:47.510 --> 00:53:50.799
come from the trenches.
California had a part-time legislature from

00:53:50.799 --> 00:53:55.670
1850 to 1967.
And then, in my opinion, California started

00:53:55.670 --> 00:54:01.739
to deteriorate as a state when a professional,
full-time legislature emerged in the early

00:54:01.739 --> 00:54:04.329
1970s.
And these professional politicians from both

00:54:04.329 --> 00:54:09.049
parties have done huge amounts of damage.
&gt;&gt;&gt; So I think that's a natural segue to the

00:54:09.049 --> 00:54:14.470
second question, which is, how do you distinguish
yourself from Governor Brown and what his

00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:18.880
campaign is?
He's clearly a professional career politician,

00:54:18.880 --> 00:54:24.099
but he at least is saying, look, we tried
the mandate with the governor, businessman

00:54:24.099 --> 00:54:25.469
who is going to come in.
That didn't work.

00:54:25.469 --> 00:54:27.210
You need a professional politician to fix
things.

00:54:27.210 --> 00:54:31.410
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: That's a great last question.
Because here, there's one of three people

00:54:31.410 --> 00:54:36.329
who will be governor, that's for sure, Jerry
Brown, Meg Whitman, or Steve Poizner.

00:54:36.329 --> 00:54:40.950
There's three people that are really vastly
different in their backgrounds and approaches.

00:54:40.950 --> 00:54:43.039
You have to love this.
Voters have choices.

00:54:43.039 --> 00:54:47.239
That's what campaigns are about is to draw
distinctions and make the choices crystal

00:54:47.239 --> 00:54:49.140
clear.
Voters have to decide.

00:54:49.140 --> 00:54:53.609
What a perfect time for an election right
now, because the state is in trouble and voters

00:54:53.609 --> 00:54:56.249
really need to give guidance, a mandate to
the next governor.

00:54:56.249 --> 00:55:03.200
You have Jerry Brown on one end of the spectrum,
40 years of political experience.

00:55:03.200 --> 00:55:07.269
He has had basically one job his whole life.
That's being in politics.

00:55:07.269 --> 00:55:12.539
And being in one elected position as another.
And some people, you know, like that extensive

00:55:12.539 --> 00:55:14.869
experience.
That's one end of the spectrum.

00:55:14.869 --> 00:55:18.519
Personally, I think a lot of voters have had
enough with career politicians.

00:55:18.519 --> 00:55:22.769
I think people are looking for someone who
actually has other experiences other than

00:55:22.769 --> 00:55:26.160
just being in politics, which takes you to
the other end of the spectrum.

00:55:26.160 --> 00:55:30.360
The other end of the spectrum is Meg Whitman,
who has no experience in politics, zero, didn't

00:55:30.360 --> 00:55:35.619
vote, never run for office, has no idea, you
know, what it's like to be in Sacramento.

00:55:35.619 --> 00:55:38.690
Likes to say all the time, "We should run
Sacramento like a business."

00:55:38.690 --> 00:55:42.839
Of course that should alert people that she
doesn't really know much about what she's

00:55:42.839 --> 00:55:46.190
talking about, because it's not a business.
It's not even set up like a business.

00:55:46.190 --> 00:55:50.299
That's not even the right analogy.
Maybe running Sacramento like a well-functioning

00:55:50.299 --> 00:55:54.170
nonprofit organization, that might be closer.
That's the other end of the spectrum.

00:55:54.170 --> 00:55:58.319
And I'm in the middle.
I think this is the sweet spot here.

00:55:58.319 --> 00:56:03.619
I have this 20 years of experience of starting
and running companies from scratch I know

00:56:03.619 --> 00:56:04.869
how to create jobs.
That's essential to get this economy back

00:56:04.869 --> 00:56:08.369
on track.
But I do have this eight years of success

00:56:08.369 --> 00:56:14.229
now in public service: In the White House
during the 9/11 crisis, in the classroom,

00:56:14.229 --> 00:56:18.000
running successfully as insurance commissioner,
being a very successful insurance commissioner.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:23.500
I think that the voters will focus in on my
hybrid skill set here and track record, and

00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:26.200
that's going to make all the difference in
the world in the outcome of this election.

00:56:26.200 --> 00:56:29.430
Thank you, all, very much for the opportunity
to be here. I really appreciate it.

00:56:29.430 --> 00:56:34.400
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: And, Mr. Commissioner, I think
all of us in California can thank you and

00:56:34.400 --> 00:56:39.390
admire you for two things.
The first is that you're an example of what

00:56:39.390 --> 00:56:44.660
is good about politics, that people care so
much about the state that they give up being

00:56:44.660 --> 00:56:49.099
an entrepreneur to do something for the better
good of the state.

00:56:49.099 --> 00:56:51.019
And you've clearly done that.
And the second is, even if people disagree,

00:56:51.019 --> 00:56:55.390
the clarity of your positions and the clarity
with which you speak, I think, is a welcome

00:56:55.390 --> 00:57:00.079
improvement in politics today.
Thank you so much for being here.

00:57:00.079 --> 00:57:02.739
&gt;&gt;Steve Poizner: Thank you, all.
&gt;&gt;Eric Schmidt: Good luck.

00:57:02.739 --> 00:57:02.779
[ Applause ]

